<TEXT>
glasnost may have come too late for east 
germanys dull dowdy newspapers and magazines 
only a few months after the revolution allowed journalists to 
switch from the communist party line to more balanced reporting 
the press faces a second upheaval west german publishers are 
trying to woo eastern readers with racy reporting and gloss 
the four mightiest representatives of west german journalism 
axel springer verlag gruener und jahr bauer and burda began 
distributing their papers and magazines throughout east germany 
this month 
gruener und jahrs hamburg headquarters said the publishers 
delivered 100000 copies on the first day of sales 
east german journalists knew when the orthodox communist 
government of erich honecker fell in october that wed be faced 
with freemarket competition that wed have to adopt more 
competitive practices said matthias schlegel deputy editor of 
the daily neue zeit 
his paper with a circulation of 150000 and a price of 20 
pfennigs 12 cents has survived only with state support 
were worried we wont be able to survive economically 
schlegel said its a real question for our existence he said 
all east german papers plan to raise prices april 1 neue zeit 
will go up to 55 pfennigs 31 cents 
east germans usually could receive west german television but 
printed material from the west was kept out for years 
then early this month the west german publishers put street 
vendors to work around east berlins alexanderplatz selling such 
journals as the masscirculation bild zeitung conservative daily 
die welt news magazines der spiegel and stern and a wide range of 
fashion and sports magazines 
roland vogel a distribution official for springer publisher of 
bildzeitung said most of the vendors were sold out by lunchtime 
every day 
for the regular vendors in the statecontrolled system its a 
different story 
we still cant sell western papers theres still been no 
agreement on prices said a man who runs a stand at the 
alexanderplatz subway station as he tidied old copies of cuba 
international and the czechoslovak motor review 
because the communistled interim government has not set the 
terms for distribution through the regular system west german 
publishers decided to use street vendors supermarkets and bakeries 
most of the western publications are priced at an exchange rate 
of three east german marks for one west german mark that means 
for example that der spiegel would cost 1350 east marks the 
equivalent of 765 
a 24yearold student who identified himself only as dieter 
said the western journals were simply too expensive for him he 
bought copies of the communist party daily neues deutschland and 
youth paper junge welt at an alexanderplatz kiosk 
juergen ludwig a railroad worker from erfurt took the opposite 
view i dont think theyre that expensive and the quality is 
definitely better especially with the magazines 
at a nearby booth jacqueline hoffmann sold subscriptions to 
berliner morgenpost a springer paper 
were offering subscriptions at 1940 marks 11 a month at a 
guaranteed 1to1 rate until currency union comes she said 
people are a bit skeptical because they dont know the paper 
but weve sold 40 subscriptions today 
economic union of the two germanys in which the west german 
mark is expected to replace the nonconvertible east german 
currency is seen as the first step toward political reunification 
east germans prefer subscriptions to buying single copies of 
papers they account for more than 90 percent of circulation for 
neue zeit schlegels paper 
resisting the western deluge will not be easy for east german 
papers most of which use old laborintensive production methods 
schlegel said there may be a spate of takeovers by west german 
press barons jockeying for market position and that small regional 
or local papers might be targets 
the east german news agency adn which surprised western 
journalists with its rapid change to fast reliable reporting is 
said to be planning a merger with the west german agency dpa 
tageszeitung a west german tabloid has set up in east berlin 
to print a separate eastern edition 
</TEXT>
