<TEXT>
in the old days east germans never dared 
step on the huge lawn in front of communist party headquarters the 
ominous center of power where 2000 functionaries controlled every 
detail of national life 
after the ouster of the hardline leaders last fall east 
berliners began to reclaim the grass for picnics and sunbathing 
sightseers would casually stroll up the steps of the huge gray 
sevenstory building 
now in the final transition from dictatorship to democracy the 
party is moving out of what was known as the house of the 
thousand telephones 
the former communist fortress will now provide office space for 
the 400 members of parliament elected sunday in east germanys 
first free vote the deadline for moving out is april 1 
today few reminders are left of the once omnipotent party 
silence has descended on the 820 rooms and miles upon miles of 
linoleumlined corridors that once bustled with bureaucrats 
the bronze busts of karl marx and friedrich engels that guarded 
the inner portals have been carted up to the attic where they 
joined discarded postersized official photographs of ousted 
party chief erich honecker 
the 16foothigh oval party emblem on the right side of the 
facade was removed by workers in january after the communists 
pledged reform and renamed themselves the party of democratic 
socialism 
the reformed party as a symbol of change has decorated the 
facade with rows of colorful paintings by west berlin artists 
during the election party on sunday children romped through the 
grand hall on the ground floor as their parents drank beer and 
cheered the new party leaders reformers gregor gysi and prime 
minister hans modrow 
the old party apparatus has been smashed and now people 
actually like to come here and enjoy themselves said sylvia 
graefe 39 a party archivist speaking in her small basement office 
only six months ago the closely guarded party fortress 
symbolized how isolated the ruling regime had become from the 
population after 41 years of totalitarian rule 
honecker and the 20 other members of the ruling politburo 
occupied offices on the second floor to which only selected 
employees had access even they needed special identification cards 
with two red stripes and had to pass numerous security guards 
before reaching the inner sanctum 
mrs graefe recalled that ordinary party workers would sometimes 
be called up to the second floor to provide a cheering section for 
foreign visitors a practice that employees referred to as the 
clapping detail 
five minutes before the visitor arrived honecker would emerge 
from his room and make a little small talk with us maybe talk 
about the weather when the visitor came honecker would embrace 
him we clapped and then the two disappeared into honeckers 
office she said 
the leaders of the party that espoused equality and brotherhood 
always remained aloof from the rankandfile communists said mrs 
graefe 
politburo members used a private woodpaneled elevator while 
party employees moved up and down in a crude elevator without 
doors politburo members lunched in an executive dining room on the 
seventh floor while mrs graefe and others stood in line with 
plastic trays in the groundfloor cafeteria 
party official jutta boehm who for 10 years headed the 
politburos typing pool blamed the selfimposed isolation of the 
77yearold honecker and his ruling clique of old men for the 
collapse of the regime 
if they had been a little more accessible things would be 
different today said mrs boehm 
the partys membership has shrunk from 25 million to about 
600000 since october 
</TEXT>
