<TEXT>
these are heady days at the hoover 
institution on war revolution and peace where scholars surrounded 
by the largest collection of soviet papers outside the kremlin hope 
to close the book on communism 
they are scouring eastern europe and the soviet union sweeping 
up papers posters and other artifacts to add to the 25 miles of 
library shelves that house everything from the first editions of 
pravda to the latest speeches by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev 
the late president hoover a lifelong foe of communism founded 
the library with his own world war i collection two years after the 
1917 soviet revolution 
today more than merely collecting hoover economists 
historians and political scientists are analyzing and playing a 
role in the transition of the soviet bloc by meeting with leaders 
of the new governments and us officials 
former secretary of state george p shultz an honorary fellow 
at hoover and us ambassador to czechoslovakia shirley temple 
black a former member of hoovers board of overseers are helping 
set up some of the meetings 
we are in a new era that is revolutionary shultz said in an 
interview in his office at hoover in the center of the stanford 
university campus 
it is fascinating to think about the problems of transition 
from one kind of system to another kind how you manage that some 
people here will be thinking about that and studying that and 
trying to be helpful to people doing that through this period i 
want to be part of that process of change 
other think tanks are similarly abuzz with scholars looking at 
upheavals overseas 
the center for strategic and international studies based in 
washington sees its mission now as helping america cope with a 
radically different world said robert e hunter vice president of 
the centers regional programs 
some of the academic cold warriors have even taken to gloating 
