guidelines to protect the wetlands 
along the lower mississippi river are slowing development and could 
reverse the economic revival sought by congress for this 
povertystricken region some officials say 
farmers plans to dig ditches build dikes or ponds and clear 
land have been put on hold and as the construction season 
approaches developers fear delays paperwork and the mitigation 
of land will increase building costs 
were just about going to miss the work season said dennis 
sorrell of bond engineering in west memphis sorrel said he has 
residential subdivisions a county health building apartment 
complexes and other industrial projects on hold 
when developers dont develop engineers dont work lumber 
companies dont sell lumber carpenters dont work he said 
under new federal guidelines developers and farmers must obtain 
a permit issued by the us army corps of engineers before turning 
a spade of dirt in the wetlands yet no section 404 permits have 
been issued in arkansas and a corps spokesman said none would be 
issued for some time 
the new no net loss policy spurred by bush administration 
efforts to comply with environmental laws states wetlands that 
have been taken over must be replaced also the amount of lands 
defined as wetlands has increased 
roughly threefourths of the region now meets the new 
definition instead of about 20 percent previously classified as 
wetlands according to the lower mississippi delta development 
commission 
ron murphy a natural resources specialist with the 
memphisbased commission said the new definition does not 
distinguish between different land 
weve got to identify that high quality wetland and then 
there needs to be some balance struck he said 
were looking into it as a major problem the wetlands policy 
is going to have a significant impact on economic development in 
the delta he said 
