<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to hear 
appeals stemming from a 200 million settlement of pricefixing 
charges against the nations leading manufacturers of folding 
cartons 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that 
redistributed a 6 million surplus from the settlement in one of 
the biggest antitrust cases ever 
the manufacturers were accused of criminal antitrust violations 
in 1975 by the justice department 
in the wake of that successful prosecution the manufacturers 
were sued by 2700 customers that suit was settled in 1979 when a 
200 million fund was created to pay off all claims 
in an unusual twist some 6 million was left over in unclaimed 
money triggering a decadelong battle that led to the appeals 
acted on today 
two federal judges in illinois hubert l will and the late 
edwin a robson ordered creation of a foundation to spend the 
surplus for research on complex antitrust and classaction lawsuits 
but the 7th us circuit court of appeals in 1984 overruled the 
judges order calling it a miscarriage of justice and an abuse 
of discretion 
the appeals court instead ordered the money turned over to the 
federal government 
but before the order was carried out the manufacturers and 
their customers worked out a new agreement that would let law 
schools apply for some of the funds judges will and robson 
approved that agreement 
loyola university in chicago was awarded 12 million and the 
university of chicago 156000 
the 7th circuit court acting on an appeal by the federal 
government ruled in 1989 that the universities must return the 
money 
the appeals court then sent the case to another federal judge to 
come up with a new solution for distributing the excess money 
the appeals court suggested the money be distributed on a 
nationwide basis perhaps by giving it to the federal judicial 
center foundation that helps educate and train court personnel and 
does research to improve the federal courts 
the appeals court ruling was challenged in separate appeals by 
will and the customers who sued the folding carton manufacturers 
in a third appeal a committee will and robson appointed to 
distribute the surplus funds asked the high court to award it 
lawyer fees denied by the 7th circuit court 
bush administration lawyers in yet another appeal said the 
high court should not disturb the appeals court ruling if the 
justices agreed to review the case the government appeal said 
they should consider giving the surplus money to the federal 
government 
the cases are in re will 89927 in re folding carton 
litigation 89992 folding carton administration committee vs 
folding carton reserve fund 891081 and us vs folding carton 
reserve fund 891097 
