<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected an appeal by 
puerto rico officials fined more than 30 million for failing to 
move quickly enough to relieve prison overcrowding 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that the 
commonwealths belated efforts to ease the problem is not reason 
enough to cancel the fines 
officials from 31 states joined in urging the justices to hear 
the commonwealths appeal 
the states are alabama arizona arkansas california delaware 
florida hawaii idaho illinois indiana kansas kentucky 
louisiana maryland michigan mississippi missouri nevada new 
mexico north carolina ohio pennsylvania rhode island south 
dakota tennessee texas vermont utah virginia west virginia 
and wyoming 
state officials said strict enforcement of such federal court 
penalties could delay voluntary prison reforms 
the puerto rico case stems from a 1979 lawsuit by inmates a 
federal judge ruled the following year that each prisoner must be 
provided at least 35 square feet of cell space temporarily and 
ultimately 55 square feet in dormitories and 70 square feet in 
individual cells 
commonwealth officials in 1986 agreed to comply with the court 
order and began to expand prison capacity 
but in july 1987 the officials were fined 50000 plus 10 per 
day per inmate for failing to provide 35 square feet of space per 
prisoner the fines were increased in august 1988 so that by 
november 1989 they approached a total of 30 million 
gov rafael hernandez colon and other officials said tropical 
rains and an unexpected increase in the prison population prevented 
them from meeting their own deadlines for easing overcrowding 
they said they inherited the problem from a previous 
administration and had more than tripled the commonwealths prison 
budget prison capacity was increased from 5400 in 1985 to 10295 
last year they said 
but the 1st us circuit court of appeals upheld the fines last 
september 
the relevant harm confinement in an area smaller than five by 
seven feet is significant the appeals court said the number 
of prisoners suffering that harm seven to 10 percent is large 
and the time since entry of the remedial decree is long 
the appeals court said officials have not shown that meeting 
their own deadline for providing the minimum space was 
overwhelmingly difficult or anywhere near impossible 
the appeals court added that us district court judge juan m 
perezgiminez who has presided over the case could decide to use 
the fines to pay for prison expansion 
puerto rico officials said if other appeals courts adopted the 
1st circuit courts approach it could mean that states and the 
federal government would have to pay billions of dollars a year in 
fines for failing to expand prisons quickly enough 
the states that supported puerto ricos appeal said nearly every 
state in the nation is under a court order to improve prison 
conditions 
the case is hernandez colon vs feliciano 891016 
</TEXT>
