the supreme court today agreed to decide how 
much authority federal judges have to rule in some labor disputes 
the court said it will hear an appeal by two workers fired by a 
michigan company ring screw works 
arthur groves was fired for allegedly excessive unexcused 
absences from work bobby evans was dismissed for allegedly 
falsifying company records 
both men denied the charges but lost grievance complaints 
against the company they then sued the firm for firing them 
without due cause in violation of the federal labor relations 
management act 
the united automobile workers union joined the lawsuits on the 
side of the employees 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals last year upheld a ruling 
by a federal judge who threw out the suits 
the appeals court said the uaw contract with ring screw works 
provides that a strike is the unions only recourse when workers 
lose grievances the appeals court said the only exception that 
would permit the workers to sue would be if they accused the union 
of breaching its duty to represent them fairly 
the fired workers made no such accusation 
the union members had voted against striking after groves and 
evans lost their grievances 
groves evans and the uaw said in their appeals to the supreme 
court that federal appeals courts elsewhere have disagreed with the 
6th circuit court and ruled that federal judges have authority to 
rule in such suits they asked the justices to resolve the conflict 
the case is groves vs ring screw works 891166 
