<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected an appeal by 
owners of a north carolina adult film and book store who hired a 
college professor to help them rebut obscenity charges 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that had the 
effect of exposing the professor to an obscenity prosecution if he 
surveyed people about their reactions to sexually explicit material 
cinema blue of charlotte nc and its owners jim st john and 
curtis renee peterson were charged in 1988 with disseminating 
obscenity st john and peterson were convicted last year and each 
was sentenced to six years in prison their store was fined 
250000 
prior to their trial the two men hired ohio state university 
sociology professor joseph e scott as an expert witness 
scott planned to show the allegedly obscene material to randomly 
selected groups of adults in mecklenburg county he also planned to 
conduct telephone surveys aimed at determining community attitudes 
toward the material 
the north carolina obscenity law bans sexually explicit material 
lacking serious literary artistic political or scientific 
value if it also is patently offensive and appeals to the 
prurient interest in sex as judged by contemporary community 
standards 
peter s gilchrist iii the local district attorney warned the 
cinema blue owners that scott could be prosecuted if he conductted 
the surveys 
a state judge refused to shield scott from prosecution and st 
john and peterson turned to the federal courts for help 
us district judge james b mcmillan ruled in their favor 
issuing an injunction that barred gilchrist from prosecuting the 
professor for conducting the surveys 
but the 4th us circuit court of appeals last year overruled 
the judge in the unique circumstances present here the 
appeals court said the judge should not have interfered in a 
pending state prosecution 
scott was not immediately threatened with any irremediable 
harm for his remedy for avoiding state prosecution lay entirely 
within his hands and could be invoked with no sacrifice of any 
federal rights personal to him the appeals court said 
the appeals court also rejected charges that the adult book 
stores proprietors were victims of unlawful discrimination by 
gilchrist the store owners said gilchrist permitted 
antipornography groups and others to conduct surveys similar to 
the one scott wanted to undertake 
the case is cinema blue vs gilchrist 891213 
