<TEXT>
chinas national legislature meets tuesday in an 
annual session expected to be devoid of controversy and laden with 
shows of loyalty to government political and economic policies 
unlike previous sessions of the national peoples congress when 
mild debate and scatterings of negative votes were taken as signs 
of emerging democracy the emphasis at the first meeting since the 
june 1989 crackdown on demonstrators will be on political stability 
and obedience 
wan li chairman of the congress standing committee has called 
on the nearly 3000 deputies to the 15day national meeting to 
follow the guidance of the ruling communist party and make 
correct policies for the good of all chinese people 
communist party members who make up about twothirds of the 
delegates reportedly have been told to refrain from making 
controversial statements or proposals at the plenum 
the congress in recent years has tried to shake off its 
rubberstamp image by openly debating and sometimes amending 
legislation but the party still holds ultimate authority to 
initiate and decide policy 
tuesdays highlight will be a stateofthenation address by 
premier li peng in which he is expected to hail the suppression of 
the prodemocracy student movement and reassert chinas commitment 
to communist party rule and socialism 
li also will pledge to continue an austerity program that has 
brought inflation under control but may announce some concessions 
such as the easing of tight money policies to pull the economy out 
of a serious slump 
li a political hardliner and economic conservative is 
unlikely to reveal plans for new economic reforms instead of 
marketoriented price reforms now politically inexpedient he may 
call for tighter management of prices 
on foreign policy matters li is expected to express chinas 
interest in good relations with all countries including the soviet 
union and the united states but stress that china will not be 
influenced by rapid changes in other socialist countries or bow to 
us demands for human rights reforms 
the deputies also will hear a report from the finance minister 
on the governments precarious financial state and approve the 1990 
budget 
attempts to balance the budget have been made more difficult by 
intense competition for limited funds bureaucrats seeking money 
for struggling education social welfare and infrastructure 
programs are vying with the military which carries more clout 
since the army put down the demonstrations and wants to reverse the 
trend of falling defense budgets 
the deputies are expected to pass with little debate a basic law 
to govern hong kong after the british colony reverts to chinese 
rule in 1997 and an amendment to the joint venture law 
guaranteeing that foreign enterprises in china will not be 
nationalized 
the congress will approve several government personnel changes 
but the standing committee spokesman yao guang on monday dampened 
speculation about major displacements including the removal of li 
the scheduled changes he said do not correspond with the 
rumors and guesses and reports of some newspapers in hong kong 
he said 
li is widely disliked because of his key role in the violent 
military suppression of the prodemocracy movement and his economic 
policies that have led to factory closures and unemployment there 
has been speculation the party would demote him to shore up its 
shaky reputation among the populace 
hong kong and foreign reports also have suggested the party 
would have a nonparty member named vice premier as part of its 
recent pledges to give those outside the party a greater voice in 
the government 
yao said the congress would take up the request by senior leader 
deng xiaoping to step down as chairman of the state central 
military commission deng still regarded as the most powerful 
person in china resigned in november as head of the largely 
overlapping party central military commission ending his official 
party duties 
communist party general secretary jiang zemin who succeeded 
deng in the party post is expected to get the state job as well 
yao said jiangs predecessor zhao ziyang who was purged form 
all party posts in june for allegedly supporting the democracy 
movement would not attend the congress 
