swallows made their 
traditional st josephs day appearance in this old mission town 
today as hundreds of residents and visitors cheered the forktailed 
birds return 
from the mission church courtyard paul arbiso 96 and frank 
velasquez 68 spotted a small group of swallows flying above the 
214yearold mission the two hometown residents pulled ropes to 
ring the four church bells to formally celebrate the birds 
migratory return from argentina 
a handful of swallows and dozens of pigeons flew from the 
mission eaves to nearby treetops during the twominute ringing of 
the bells 
its fun its like playing pulling the ropes and all 
said arbiso who has sighted the swallows return for several 
decades 
swallows had been seen earlier this morning but by tradition 
arbisos sighting signals their official return 
the swallow watch began in a thick fog shortly after dawn 
kicking off a series of celebrations that end with the fiesta de 
las golondrinas parade on saturday the morning fog slowly burned 
off to reveal a clear blue sky 
arbiso like others present said the numbers of swallows were 
decreasing 
twenty or thirty years ago they were all over flocks of them 
coming in and out id sure like to see those days again he said 
first accounts of the swallows coming to san juan capistrano 
date back to 1776 that was the year father junipero serra founded 
the mission as part of spains effort to spread the roman catholic 
faith in the new world 
the traditional belief that the birds return every st josephs 
day gained widespread fame because of a hit 1939 song when the 
swallows come back to capistrano according to legend the 
swallows failed to arrive in capistrano only once in 1935 when 
they were held up by a storm 
in the fall the swallows migrate to goya argentina about 
5000 miles to the south 
