<TEXT>
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki is 
coming to the united states to seek support for the solidarityled 
governments demand that a treaty guaranteeing polands western 
border be signed before germany unifies 
the former solidarity editor and political prisoner leaves 
warsaw on tuesday for a sixday visit to the united states with a 
oneday stop in canada it will be mazowieckis longest abroad 
since he was elected in august to lead the first noncommunist 
government in the east bloc 
i dont need to stress the significance of the visit for 
poland to a country which is the worlds no 1 superpower 
government spokeswoman malgorzata niezabitowska said recently 
outlining the goals of the visit 
mazowiecki achieved one aim of his trip when the four victorious 
world war ii allies and the two germanys last week decided to allow 
poland to take part in sessions of twoplusfour talks that 
concern polands security 
now mazowiecki will be pushing for us backing of his 
governments demand that a treaty guaranteeing polands western 
border be initialed by east germany and west germany before 
unification and then ratified by a unified germany 
treaties commit the germanys to respect the oder and neisse 
rivers as polands western border but a unified germany is not 
bound by those terms 
poles are concerned by some in germany who urge reunification be 
sought within the 1937 borders that included about onethird of 
presentday poland 
warsaw has not been satisfied by a resolution backed by west 
german chancellor helmut kohl asking parliaments in west germany 
and east germany to adopt declarations saying a united germany 
should sign a treaty affirming the poles right to live in secure 
borders 
we would like the us to act towards stabilization of 
transformations taking place in europe and to support as it has 
always done the polish interests particularly those concerning 
the process of german unification janusz onyszkiewicz former 
solidarity spokesman and now a deputy to parliament told the pap 
news agency monday 
germany unity developments in central europe security and 
defense issues and economic cooperation are expected to be the 
topics of talks between mazowiecki and president bush 
prospects for polishamerican cooperation are better today 
than at any time since the end of world war ii this new attitude 
results from what happened and is happening in poland and that 
washington has appreciated the importance of polish events said 
a commentary monday in the zycie warszawy newspaper 
mazowiecki also is to meet with us defense secretary dick 
cheney treasury secretary nicholas brady members of congress and 
other top us officials 
mazowiecki a lawyer practicing roman catholic and top adviser 
to solidarity leader lech walesa for a decade is expected to focus 
on talks rather than the public appearances that characterized 
walesas trip to the united states in november 
niezabitowska said mazowiecki is to address the council on 
foreign relations and meet with representatives of jewish 
organizations and groups of american poles 
mazowiecki also will be pursuing increased financial aid and 
cooperation for his radical economic reform program 
with the blessing of the world bank and the international 
monetary fund the solidarityled government introduced a 
promarket reform plan jan 1 that lifted most price controls 
ended many government subsidies to industry and made the zloty a 
convertible currency 
niezabitowska said mazowiecki plans to extend polands thanks 
for the help it has received from the united states in direct aid 
and in dealings with the paris club the world bank and the 
international monetary fund 
further assistance in restructuring polands 41 billion debt 
31 billion of which is owed to the united states also is 
expected to be discussed 
mazowiecki also will be seeking a reduction of restrictions on 
technology imports a broadening of us business investment in 
poland and expansion of credit guarantees 
warsaw would like washington to lift travel restrictions placed 
on polish diplomats following the 1981 martiallaw crackdown to 
crush solidarity 
it also would like to open a consulate in california where many 
polish emigres have settled as well as an easing of us 
restrictions on issuing visas to poles niezabitowska said more 
than 60 percent of all polish applications for us visas are 
rejected 
mazowiecki will travel to canada for one day after his us trip 
for talks with canadian officials 
