dotted with pinon and juniper colorful wall paintings of kiowa 
rituals and hopi kachina figures are washing into the red dirt 
rain and snow fall through what once was a conical roof eating 
away the indian murals a brave raises his arms toward a buffalo 
another beats a drum dancers chant and hold prayer wands a 
funeral procession makes its way 
vanishing with them is part of the history of naturalist ernest 
thompson seton who founded the woodcraft indians organization at 
the turn of the century championed indians when many saw them as 
red devils and who built the navajo hogan as part of his college 
of indian wisdom in the 1930s 
the britishborn canadianraised seton was 70 in 1930 when he 
bought 2500 acres of land near santa fe to build seton village an 
artist colony and cultural center 
a national historic landmark since 1966 seton village includes 
the 30room stone seton castle a kiva or ceremonial chamber 
decorated with the plumed serpent of the san ildefonso indian 
pueblo and the circular navajo hogan with the damaged murals 
it was painted by a kiowa indian named jack hokeah who was at 
the indian school in santa fe said dee seton barber setons 
daughter the hogan was for public ceremonies a campfire and 
stories a dance demonstration or whatever a woodcraft council 
mrs barber who still lives in seton castle said she had the 
hogan reroofed 18 years ago but cant afford to do it again 
time weather and vandals have nearly destroyed it 
seton built his rambling mansion after a lifetime as an author 
illustrator naturalist and lecturer it was designed to house his 
library of 40000 books nearly 3000 paintings and drawings and 
3000 bird and animal skins 
he wrote hundreds of books and articles including wild 
animals i have known two little savages and the first boy 
scout manual 
he hobnobbed with teddy roosevelt and mark twain helped found 
the american boy scouts and was named their first chief scout but 
he fell out with roosevelt and scouting leaders because he believed 
the movement had turned too militaristic in world war i 
he urged the government to give back indian hunting grounds 
helped southwestern indians support themselves through 
traditionbased pottery textiles and jewelry rather than cheap 
tourist knickknacks and brought indians to seton village to share 
their traditions songs stories and art 
he adopted his daughter in 1938 when he was 78 
at its height the village had a zoo a museum a craft shop 
dining hall log cabins and adobe houses up to 150 people could 
gather youngsters studying indian lore seton lecturing to adults 
on the virtues of outdoor life his wife julia beating a drum and 
singing an evening chant at lights out 
snapshots taken in the 1930s and 1940s show intricate wood 
carvings over entrances to dorms and the dining hall long rows of 
tepees a thriving vegetable garden 
many adobe houses remain some rebuilt and expanded other 
buildings including the dining hall dorms and dance lodge are 
gone and the hogan nearly so 
the national park service oversees national historic landmarks 
but has no repair money for them it reported in 1986 that the 
outside of the hogan could be patched for 6000 it also 
recommended spending 2800 to have an art conservator evaluate the 
paintings inside before restoring them 
the kiva with the plumed serpent painting circling its inner 
wall at that time needed 5450 in exterior work plus interior 
repairs evaluation and outside grading costing an estimated 2300 
those findings were made in a landmarks at risk report 
soliciting donations to the national park foundation which 
administers private contributions for the park service 
but we were unsuccessful with seton village said gregory d 
kendrick chief of the history unit at the park services rocky 
mountain regional office 
now the weather and vandal damage to the hogan is far more 
severe and its unclear whether any of the murals can be saved 
i dont even go out there anymore said mrs barber it 
just makes me sick 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

