the supreme court today refused to become 
embroiled in a fight between environmentalists and the bush 
administration over oregon timber and the northern spotted owl 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that threw out 
part of a lawsuit seeking to protect the owl from the asserted 
threat posed by logging operations in the old forests of westalership sentenced 
under the law to six months 
in prison 
refused to hear appeals stemming from a 200 million 
settlement of pricefixing charges against the nations leading 
manufacturers of folding cartons 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that 
redistributed a 6 million surplus from the settlement in one of 
the biggest antitrust cases ever 
refused to hear a bush administration appeal aimed at making 
it costlier for an organization called the national security 
archive to compile information 
the archive is a nonprofit organization that collects 
information on national security and foreign policy and makes it 
available to the public in various ways it has filed thousands of 
foia requests for government records 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that gives the 
archive the same preferential status under the freedom of 
information act that other news media enjoy 
the us fish and wildlife service estimates that about 1500 
breeding pairs of northern spotted owls remain and that without 
protection their numbers could be cut in half by the year 2050 
the owl is being considered for inclusion on the federal 
governments endangered species list 
a coalition of environmental groups including the various 
audubon society chapters the wilderness society the sierra club 
and the natural resources defense council sued the interior 
department in 1987 over timbermanagement plans for the western 
oregon forests 
the lawsuit alleged that the departments bureau of land 
management had decided to continue logging oldgrowth timber 
without adequately considering the detrimental effects to the 
spotted owl population 
the governments decision therefore was made in violation of 
four federal laws the national environmental policy act nepa 
the oregon and california lands act the federal land policy and 
management act and the migratory bird treaty act 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals last september dismissed 
that portion of the lawsuit alleging a nepa violation ruling that 
congress had precluded such a court challenge when it passed a 1988 
appropriations bill for the interior department 
the appeal acted on today argued that the appeals court wrongly 
interpreted the 1988 legislation 
the 9th circuit court sent the lawsuit back to us district 
judge helen j frye in oregon for consideration of the claims 
raised under the three other environmental laws 
while the case was pending before frye congress last october 
passed a 1990 appropriations bill dealing with timber production on 
federal lands and protecting the northern spotted owl 
the bill specifically states that the bureau of land 
managements consideration of logging effects on the owl is 
adequate for the purpose of meeting the statutory requirements 
that are the basis for the 1987 lawsuit 
judge frey last dec 21 dismissed the lawsuits remaining claims 
without prejudice to the filing of any new action challenging the 
blm owl management activities after fiscal year 1990 
an appeal in which the environmental groups are mounting a 
constitutional attack against the 1990 appropriations bill is 
pending in the 9th circuit court 
the case acted on today is portland audubon society vs lujan 
89931 
