chancellor helmut kohl said monday a 
unified european economy should include the soviet bloc and a new 
system for settling potential military conflicts 
kohls comments came at the opening of an eastwest security 
conference that is to focus on the economic recovery of eastern 
european nations that have overthrown their communist regimes in 
the past year 
the conference is the biggest gathering of east and west nations 
since the opening of the berlin wall and it came one day after 
east germans in their first free elections chose a government 
that is likely to embrace kohls plan for a swift reunification of 
the germanys 
kohl called for european nations to form a security agency that 
would mediate conflicts and another agency to verify arms control 
agreements 
we need an instrument that makes it possible to prevent 
conflicts while they are still in the bud kohl told the 
conference on security and cooperation in europe the 35nation 
group includes the united states canada and all eastern and 
western european nations except albania 
a european conflict center and a center for verifying arms 
control agreements could be the first steps toward building up 
comprehensive security structures in europe he said 
he gave few details of the new security agencies but said they 
should be within the framework of the conference which 
includes the soviet union 
kohl however reiterated his opposition to neutrality for a 
unified germany and said the merged nation should continue to 
belong to nato the soviet union is seeking neutrality for a united 
germany 
kohl also urged the west to help stabilize eastern europes new 
attempts at freemarket economies and promote their integration 
with the rest of europe 
he said he supports the idea of forging treaties of 
association that would tighten economic ties between east and 
west europe 
he also said the west should help create conditions for a 
paneuropean economic area that would bring the economies of 
europe closer together 
the eastwest meeting in bonn which runs until april 11 will 
include the participation of more than 600 business and government 
officials from eastern and western europe 
