talks with the usbacked rebels it has been battling for 15 years 
eduard a shevardnadze made his comments before ending a 24hour 
visit to this country during the first trip to subsaharan africa 
by a soviet chief of diplomacy 
given the dynamic and rapid changes in the world recently 
it shouldnt be impossible to start renewed direct peace 
negotiations in the coming months shevardnadze told reporters 
after a twohour meeting with president jose eduardo dos santos 
he said a final peace accord could be signed by the time cuba 
completes the scheduled withdrawal of its estimated 50000 troops 
from angola by july 1 1991 
despite shevardnadzes remarks hopes for a quick peace seem 
faint earlier peace talks and a june truce have collapsed and 
fighting has intensified since the government launched an offensive 
in december 
western diplomats here noting the recent warming of ussoviet 
relations are expecting the superpowers to put more pressure on 
the angolan adversaries to come to peace 
shevardnadze left angola later monday for the zambian capital 
