<TEXT>
the head of nasas space flight program 
acknowledged monday that repair and maintenance problems exist in 
the planned space station but said they can be fixed by design 
changes long before the station is built 
im not worried about it said bill lenoir the space 
agencys associate administrator for space flight its one of 
many things at this point in the design that is inherently fuzzy 
a report in mondays new york times said nasa discovered 
belatedly that the station planned for assembly beginning in 1995 
would require about 2200 hours of maintenance each year by 
astronauts working in the hazardous open space environment 
lenoir said a more realistic but still inflated estimate is 
550 hours which he also considers too much 
at this point admittedly we dont understand in depth the 
reliability of the subsystems and pieces of subsystems he said 
in an interview so weve made some unrealistic assumptions like 
everything that can fail will fail and it will fail once a year 
then we multiply it all together and say well gee thats 
550 hours we know thats harsh and probably higher than realistic 
and thats what well be spending between now and december working 
on lenoir said the figure is exaggerated even more he said by 
being multiplied by four to 2200 hours 
the times said nasa investigators discovered the setback 
early this year but lenoir said it has been an issue thats been 
worked on for six months and part of a preliminary design process 
that will continue until a review in december 
weve taken this quick and dirty bottomsup assessment and now 
we are going to dig in itembyitem and say whats the real 
requirement and how will we deal with it lenoir said 
i wouldnt say im not worried about it but im worried about 
it no more than anything else im paid to worry about everything 
the newspapers report said there were 5578 parts outside the 
stations inhabited modules that could be replaced if they failed 
and that those calculations increased the work load by 30 percent 
lenoir said maintenance and repair of any such items can be 
planned in four ways 
i can live with it i can do it robotically i can make it 
require less maintenance by upping its reliability or i can move 
it inside the pressurized living module so it becomes an 
intravehicular rather than an extravehicular job 
lenoir said it would be wrong to think the space station has a 
major problem when in fact we have a minor problem business as 
usual we are working on it and we are on schedule for coping with 
it 
