yosef is an israeli former chief rabbi of sephardic jews those 
of middle east or north african origin who now constitute a 
majority in israel 
born in baghdad iraqs capital he served as deputy chief rabbi 
of egypt before moving to israel here he was a religious court 
judge author of studies of jewish religious writings and founder 
in 1984 of shas an acronym for the sephardic torah guardians 
he created the party in reaction to what was perceived as 
discrimination against religious sephardic jews by the 
ultraorthodox religious establishment which was dominated by 
ashkenazis or european jews 
shas quickly gained support among secular sephardis as well 
today with six seats it is the third largest party in the 
120seat knesset or parliament three other religious parties 
control 12 seats 
sephardic jews comprise roughly 55 percent of israels jewish 
population they generally are poorer and more conservative than 
ashkenazi jews their overwhelming support enabled the likud to end 
29 years of rule by the centerleft labor party in 1977 
but since the 27monthold intefadeh or palestinian uprising 
has made peace a more urgent concern yosef and some other 
sephardic leaders have surprised their flock with moderate 
statements 
first yosef on a festive homecoming to egypt last summer 
declared that he believed the religious commandment to prevent 
bloodshed superseded israels right to the occupied territories 
then a few months ago another sephardic spiritual leader 
baba baruch abuhatzeira went further and advocated talks with 
the palestine liberation organization which israel views as a 
terrorist organization 
both sephardic and ashkenazi spiritual leaders have generally 
exhibited concern primarily for matters of immediate interest to 
their flocks funding for religious schools and housing and 
demands to pass legislation favorable to religion 
that is why it was surprising yosef got involved in the larger 
political question of how israel should make peace with the arabs 
