<TEXT>
seabrook nuclear power plant operators on 
monday began what was considered the first step toward initiating a 
sustained atomic reaction in the plants uranium fuel 
operators began diluting neutronabsorbing boron in the 
reactors primary cooling system setting the stage for withdrawing 
the 57 control rods from the reactor spokesman ron sher said 
withdrawing the control rods which also absorb neutrons would 
raise the number of stray neutrons in the reactor core enough to 
begin a sustained chain reaction of fissioning uranium atoms 
sher said the first fission in the fuel core since lowpower 
testing in mid1989 would follow within tens of minutes with 
the reactor operating at a fraction of 1 percent of full power 
sher said monday afternoon that withdrawing the rods was some 
time away but could come early tuesday he said the timetable 
was difficult to predict because plant personnel also were 
performing final rounds of instrument and equipment checks 
he said its difficult to say precisely when the plant will move 
beyond the system check mode because somebody doesnt say 
okay now were in the startup mode but sher said earlier this 
month that diluting the boron could be considered the first 
physical step toward initiating a chain reaction 
the 65 billion plant finished in mid1986 finally got its 
nuclear regulatory commission operating license on thursday 
following lengthy regulatory battles and a preliminary court 
skirmish decided in seabrooks favor 
the us court of appeals in washington declined last week to 
block the license pending further court action but still must 
consider an appeal filed by the massachusetts attorney general 
seacoast antipollution league and new england coalition on nuclear 
pollution 
</TEXT>
