<TEXT>
the japanese love to complain about their public 
broadcasting behemoth nhk and millions have stopped paying the 
fees that keep it on the air 
a lawsuit has been filed against the network because of alleged 
political partisanship by one of its prominent reporters as for 
nonpayment of fees an nhk spokesman said we dont seek 
punishment for those who refuse we just appeal to their honest 
nature 
the 66yearold japan broadcasting corp better known as 
nippon hoso kyokai or nhk is japans only national television 
network monthly fees paid by owners of television sets are 
supposed to cover its operating costs 
nhk has a generalinterest channel and another featuring science 
and cultural programs it is known for conservative programming and 
unsmiling announcers who apologize with deep bows even for minor 
mistakes in subtitles 
no advertisements appear on nhks channels nor does it mention 
brand names the title of a popular song bright red porsche 
was changed on a variety show to bright red car 
such programs as documentaries on the silk road chinas yellow 
river and the human body are acclaimed but viewers say hourslong 
live broadcasts of parliamentary debates are stultifying 
critics also say the network is too close to the governing 
liberal democratic party 
if nhk were an ordinary company the liberal democrats would 
be the majority stockholders media critic masanori atsuta said 
according to themis magazine 
a cabinetappointed committee names nhks chairman and 
parliament approves the budget nhk insists it is independent 
otherwise but investigative reporting that could embarrass the 
government is left to commercial networks 
the network has a staff of 15000 and 93 percent of its budget 
comes from public fees it regularly loses money because of the 
millions who refuse to pay 
daijiro hashimoto an nhk reporter and younger brother of 
finance minister ryutaro hashimoto is at the focus of the 
networks latest woes 
hashimoto the reporter took part in his brothers successful 
campaign for reelection to parliament in february prompting 
allegations that he violated media guidelines of political 
neutrality 
takehiro motohashi spokesman for nhk said the network 
regretted its reporters actions but was not taking 
disciplinary measures 
yokohama lawyer masayoshi hamada was sufficiantly angry to bring 
legal action against the network his suit claims nhk showed 
favoritism by lending its name to a political campaign and thus 
has no claim to user fees 
nhk will not comment on the case but spokesman motohashi made 
the appeal to peoples honest nature after noting that the 
broadcast law requires the 33 million households with television to 
pay the appropriate fees 
fees are 713 a month for a color televisions and 470 for 
blackandwhite sets payable either a year in advance or by 
monthly automatic bank transfers 
despite an income last year of 26 billion nhk ran a deficit 
of 167 million because of such costly new ventures as satellite 
broadcasting highdefinition tv and teletext broadcasting news 
reports say the network wants a 28 percent rate increase 
to mark households that pay their fees nhk puts small stickers 
on front doors one antipayment group sends out free stickers 
saying nhk fee refuser 
i paid until about three years ago said keiko watanabe a 
