<TEXT>
as she completes a decade in congress 
protecting the environment remains a top priority for rep claudine 
schneider of rhode island an activist who made her name fighting 
against a nuclear power plant in the 1970s 
the rest of congress is catching up as lawmakers rush to 
introduce bills to save the rain forest stop global warming and 
promote energy efficiency 
but schneider still is a step ahead promoting the 
restructuring of us defense forces to provide for what she calls 
american ecosecurity in the face of new environmental threats 
the country must prepare to defend itself against threats posed 
by a growing population in a world with shrinking resources 
schneider says the threats will arise she says as soil erodes 
and deserts creep into oncefertile regions triggering famines 
hungry people cross borders you get regional conflict we 
need rapid deployment forces for deserts and the tropics says 
schneider providing ecosecurity will require a complete 
reassessment of our national defense strategy she says 
schneider a republican has been a staunch environmental 
crusader throughout her career she has introduced legislation on 
such disparate environmental issues as global warming the loss of 
tropical forests the destruction of the stratospheric ozone layer 
ocean dumping oil spills and hazardous wastes 
bills she has introduced to ban ocean dumping encourage energy 
efficiency by utilities and set energy standards for home 
appliances have become law 
on march 17 the national wildlife federation gave her its 1989 
national conservation achievement award for legislation 
recognizing her outstanding leadership on a variety of 
conservation and environmental issues 
she now is lobbying the environmental protection agency to 
institute a wasteend fee that would encourage industry to recycle 
its wastes rather than dump them 
we have the technology to recycle 75 percent of our waste 
she says the question is why arent we doing it 
as the nation prepares to celebrate the 20th anniversary of 
earth day on april 22 congress suddenly is brimming with ideas to 
help the environment schneider says 
there are a dozen different approaches she says 
legislators are considering bills to provide for the planting of 
trees in cities encourage energy efficiency direct the world bank 
to promote conservation and double the budget of the united nations 
family planning program 
i think were going to see more environmental programs 
focusing on international assistance she says 
the focus of legislation in the 1990s will shift from 
controlling pollution to preventing it through such measures as 
encouraging energy efficiency she predicts 
pollution prevention pays she says leastcost energy is 
our promise for the future for domestic and foreign policy 
socalled leastcost utility planning encourages utilities 
to choose the most economical alternatives in providing new sources 
of energy it turns out schneider says that improving energy 
efficiency freeing wasted energy for new uses usually is 
cheaper than building new power plants 
at the same time boosting efficiency cuts emissions of carbon 
and sulfur dioxides responsible for global warming and acid rain 
its a winwin situation she says 
schneider developed her ideas on ecosecurity when she was asked 
three weeks ago to speak to a group of new york businessmen on the 
possible uses of the peace dividend arising from defense 
cutbacks as eastwest tensions subside 
i said theres another dynamic we should be thinking of 
eightythree percent of the worlds population growth by 2010 will 
be in china and the the tropics the resource base is limited 
certainly a piece of the national security picture for the future 
must take population into account 
environmental organizations have come to the same realization 
more of the environmental groups are taking on the population 
issue she says 
schneider made her name in her home state in 1973 as the founder 
of the rhode island committee on energy a group that opposed and 
eventually halted construction of a nuclear plant in charlestown 
ri 
from 1973 until 1978 she was founder and executive director of 
the conservation law foundation formed to represent citizens in 
environmental disputes in 1977 she became federal coordinator of 
the rhode island coastal zone management program 
she has traveled to wilderness areas in madagascar and new 
guinea and has penetrated deeper into the amazon than any us 
government official since theodore roosevelt 
the 1990s schneider says will be the decade of information 
transfer the time to get the word out about new energyefficiency 
technology developed in the 1970s and 1980s 
as part of a publicinformation campaign she soon will have her 
capitol hill office outfitted with the latest in energyefficiency 
lighting including compact fluorescent bulbs that screw into 
ordinary incandescent bulb sockets providing just as much light 
using onefourth the energy 
my frustration as a member of the science and technology 
committee for the past 10 years has been to witness the development 
of these technologies and seeing we do not have a good means as a 
government to get the information out she says 
or a means to remove practical roadblocks as she found out when 
she decided to redo her office 
it took three years to get the architect of the capitol to 
approve it she says its a situation again where we have 
the technology and we havent transferred it 
the 1990s are a transfer time she says there are no 
white hats or black hats were all in this environment together 
</TEXT>
