in a state where not so long ago many rural 
counties cut the school year to eight months instead of nine so 
the children would have more time to work in the cotton fields 
education has been moved to the front burner mississippi is 
learning but the state still has a long way to climb to get out of 
last place 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
down here at the bottom of americas 
statistics the burning issue is no longer race 
in an evolution as long coming as a magnolia spring the state 
has reckoned that the three rs of the schoolhouse not the fourth 
r of racism are the key to its future the alternative is 
chronic third worldism 
in this climate of introspection jim crow isnt dead just 
irrelevant 
the cost of the states stubborn sometimes bloody past when 
race darkened almost any aspect of public policy or private 
attitudes is embarrassingly high the highest illiteracy rate a 
third of its adults in the nation the highest school dropout 
rate the lowest score on military entrance tests 
thirty percent of mississippis high school graduates dont test 
high enough to qualify for public college in 198589 less than 
half of the college freshmen graduated 
im tired of hearing mississippi this mississippi that 
says marjorie vaughan feisty superintendent of yazoo county 
schools im tired of hearing that word bottom we have 
problems but were all working on them both races 
margie vaughan is right 
in a state where james meredith was shot 24 years ago trying to 
enroll at ole miss 65 percent of the slim public purse is now 
spent on education integrated education the legislature is 
currently scratching its head over how to raise 382 million to 
finance a threeyear education reform package proposed by gov ray 
mabus a 41yearold native back home from harvard law school and a 
washington legal firm 
this is a legislature that traditionally thinks slow and 
thinks small says ole miss history professor david sansing but 
the saliva test for public office in mississippi today is where you 
stand on schooling not segregation 
mabus hoped to pay for a third of his program with a state 
