<TEXT>
margaret walker alexander at 74 is a 
living time capsule of the agony of black education in mississippi 
her greatgrandfather was a literate freed blacksmith in georgia 
who fell in love with a slave while shoeing horses on a plantation 
one of their children became a baptist minister and helped found a 
negro college in an abandoned hospital in natchez that became 
jackson state 
as a child she knew the insides of one of the 4000 little white 
schoolhouses built for blacks in the south by the philanthropy of 
sears and roebuck millionaire julius rosenwald 
mrs alexander got two degrees from northwestern came back to 
jackson state to teach and has written poetry a novel and a 
biography of black novelist richard wright author of native 
son she lives on a street in jackson that is named for her 
ive seen three revolutions in my time the new deal civil 
rights and the electronic age she says my grandparents said 
education was the most important my grandchildren say education is 
not enough there has to be economic accessibility 
