<DOCNO> AP900319-0227 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
michael cates is an expert in tax planning and 
management for the denverbased college for financial planning a 
nonprofit institution offering financial services and educational 
programs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as they agonize over yet another tax season and an 
april 15 deadline taxpayers should remember that with careful 
planning many taxsaving ideas are available 
following are three significant taxsaving tips for people over 
55 that should be considered when preparing returns 
sale of a home 
if you sold your home during 1989 there are several options if 
the sale resulted in a loss the loss generally is a nondeductable 
personal loss however a gain on the sale may qualify for special 
tax treatment 
if a taxpayer buys a new principal residence within two years of 
the date of sale of the old principal residence the taxpayer will 
not be required to pay tax on all the gain from the sale the 
taxpayer will pay tax on the gain only to the extent that the 
adjusted sales price of the old residence exceeds the cost of 
the new one the adjusted sales price equals the selling price 
of the residence reduced by sales expenses such as advertising 
commissions and legal fees and further reduced by expenses for 
decorating and repairing to help sell the old home 
only expenses for work performed within 90 days before the 
contract to sell was signed and paid for within 30 days after the 
sale qualify capital expenses such as permanent improvements or 
replacements are added to the value of the home 
if the cost of the new residence exceeds the adjusted sales 
price of the old one no tax is paid on the sale this is known as 
a rollover of the gain or a section 1034 exchange this treatment 
is automatic if a new home is purchased in this situation the 
basis tax cost of the new residence will be reduced by the amount 
of gain postponed 
if the taxpayer sells a principal residence but does not replace 
it it still may be possible to qualify for special tax treatment 
if the taxpayer is 55 or older on the date of the sale he or she 
may be able to exclude up to 125000 of gain on the sale also the 
taxpayer must have used the residence as his or her main home 
for at least three years during the five years before the sale the 
election to exclude the gain from the sale is available only once 
in a lifetime and is made on part 1 of form 2119 
standard deductions and additional considerations 
the taxpayer is allowed to deduct the greater of the standard 
deduction or total itemized deductions the amount of the standard 
deduction is dependent upon the taxpayers filing status 
married couples filing jointly are entitled to a 5200 standard 
deduction single taxpayers are entitled to a 3100 standard 
deduction the standard deduction for heads of households is 
4550 and for married people filing separately 2600 
in addition married people who are 65 or older or blind are 
entitled to an additional standard deduction of 600 1200 if 
both 65 and blind single taxpayers who are 65 or older or blind 
are entitled to an additional standard deduction of 750 1500 if 
both 
if the taxpayer was completely blind as of dec 31 1989 a 
statement should be attached to the tax return describing the 
condition if the taxpayer was partially blind a certified 
statement from an eye doctor must be attached to the return the 
attachment must state that the taxpayers vision cannot be 
corrected with glasses or contacts to be better than 20200 in the 
better eye or that the taxpayers field of vision is 20 degrees or 
less 
medicare surtax 
finally for taxpayers eligible for medicare congress repealed 
the medicare catastrophic coverage act in december because the 
1989 tax forms were published before the repeal lines are included 
on the form that reflect the supplemental medicare surtax line 54 
on form 1040 and line 23 on form 1040a in filling out the return 
taxpayers may leave the line blank or fill it in with a zero 
if taxpayers already have made payments through additional 
estimated tax payments or additional withholdings they are 
entitled to a refund even if no income tax is owed a return must 
be filed to get a refund 
a credit for amounts paid through withholding can be claimed by 
reflecting those amounts on line 56 of form 1040 or line 25a of 
form 1040a the additions made through estimated tax payments can 
be shown on line 57 of form 1040 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

