<TEXT>
dan rostenkowski is a comfortable old 
politician a powerful house committee chairman with a huge staff 
a doting legion of lobbyists and a million bucks in his campaign 
chest with no challenger in sight 
maybe thats the kind of pol it takes to kick new life into a 
budget debate which until now has produced only stalemate and 
fiscal chicanery 
the illinois democrat known more for his clout than his daring 
last week entered the seemingly hopeless budget struggle with a 
splash to eliminate the 100 billionplus federal deficits he 
called on all sides to abandon their longheld positions his 
advice includes 
president bush raise income taxes 
democrats cut social security 
pentagon reduce spending 
bureaucrats freeze programs 
lobbyists the store is closed 
its what some call a gore everyones ox strategy to the 
tune of 500 billion over five years 
the proposal to freeze social security costofliving 
adjustments seems a thumbed nose to the elderly who offended by 
rostenkowskis support of the nowdefunct catastrophic health care 
plan attacked his car last year the domestic spending freeze 
tells fellow democrats to forget about spending any peace 
dividend from defense cuts made in the wake of the eastern 
european revolution 
by ruling out any tax cut rostenkowski rejects an idea 
popularized in his own party by sen daniel p moynihan dny 
who suggests cutting social security taxes rather than using the 
revenue to cut the deficit 
some within my own party decided they should fight 
irresponsibility with irresponsibility rostenkowski said 
rostenkowski began selling the plan this past weekend in 
speeches before some of the very interest groups who have made his 
life so comfortable with generous speaking fees and campaign 
donations 
the question is whether i can convince you that deficit 
reduction and a healthy economy are more important for your 
business than such special incentives as tax breaks he told the 
midcontinent oil and gas association 
rostenkowskis proposal to raise income taxes on the wealthy 
isnt just a challenge to bush it also abandons his own efforts to 
protect the 1986 tax reform bill that probably will be cited as 
the most sweeping achievement in rostenkowskis three decades in 
congress 
in an interview rostenkowski pushed aside questions seeking a 
personal agenda in his plan 
youve got to accept the fact that im viewed as the chairman 
of the committee that has 75 percent of the deficitreduction 
legislation in its jurisdiction he said 
im supposed to provide some leadership or some cover i 
just felt my colleagues would expect this of me he said 
rostenkowski was not too modest to suggest that he might provide 
some leadership for bush many of us felt that president bushs 
commitment to no new taxes was only a oneyear commitment he 
said 
distrust is the biggest obstacle to a deficitreduction plan 
this year he said that distrust has a long history 
many in congress both democrats and republicans proposed 
similarly daring plans in the mid1980s the republicans lost 
control of the senate after their 1985 budget proposed social 
security cuts and former house speaker jim wright was vilified for 
proposing tax increases while congress was getting a pay increase 
like others before him rostenkowski says there is the basis 
for doing something like this if everyone will step forward at the 
same time so far rostenkowski is marching alone 
bush greeted the plan with enough rhetorical warmth to keep it 
alive but refused to compromise his positions loyal house 
republicans portrayed it as another example of democrats wanting to 
raise taxes 
rostenkowskis democratic colleagues meantime praised him as 
brave but called his plan unrealistic until bush changes his tune 
some were distrustful of rostenkowskis chummy relationship with 
bush 
everyone is suspicious of the president rostenkowski said 
without bushs overt support rostenkowski concedes any deficit 
reduction plan is dead but he believes the president blinked a 
little bit this time 
rumored to be considering retirement rostenkowski seems worried 
about his generations legacy a legacy thus far of debt and a 
declining standard of living and he hopes bush and the senior 
members of congress also are worried enough to go to camp david 
and stamp something out that both republicans and democrats 
could accept 
where others see only deadlock rostenkowski sees potential for 
compromise and progress maybe he thinks he has the right 
combination of skill clout and personal security to win and 
maybe just by shaking up a moribund debate he already has 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
steven komarow covers congress for the 
associated press 
