<TEXT>
are americans buying houses at the expense of 
their homes 
the question is not as foolish as it might seem especially if 
you accept the definition of a house as a mere physical structure 
and a home as a spiritual haven and family environment 
pressured by prices that take a bigger chunk of paychecks than 
they used to both husband and wife must work to finance the house 
leaving too little time to develop the house as a home 
the consequences arent limited to the immediate family but are 
showing up as increased demands on employers and their benefits 
structure 
some businesses say the situation results in more absences and 
in stressrelated illnesses although definitive statistical 
evidence has yet to be developed the suspicion is that health 
insurance costs are being driven up 
businesses in areas where good employees are hard to find are 
either installing or contemplating daycare facilities maternal 
leave time is a standard paragraph in employment contracts 
paternal leave time is growing 
in turn critics of parental leave say it is an important factor 
in the slow growth of productivity in the american workplace they 
are preparing to counter what seems to be growing sentiment in 
congress to make it mandatory 
the national federation of indpendent business for example 
claims that mandated parental or maternity leave will prove too 
expensive for smaller companies and may discourage them from hiring 
potential parents 
whatever the problems or potential problems housing and real 
estate people suggest they arise from the fact that houses today 
often are priced so high that it takes the financial capability of 
both spouses 
citing a study by the chicago title and trust co which 
provides title insurance on houses the national association of 
realtors says the great majority of buyers last year were 
twoincome families 
the chicago study indicated that 793 percent of all couples 
buying houses last year relied on two incomes among firsttime 
buyers the percentage was 868 percent and even among repeat 
buyers it was nearly 75 percent 
the impact on family life is bound to be the of subject of 
growing study and controversy 
for one thing various other studies suggest that even todays 
socalled liberated women often are unable to reduce their load of 
household chores because men have not been sharing them that is 
women go to work and come home to work 
the consequences raise various possibilities among them that 
the effect will be felt in the emotional and phsyical health of 
children and in the quality of marital relationships 
business is watching the situation carefully fearful that 
congress will force parental leave into the cafeteria of employee 
benefits the national federation says it would make employees wary 
of hiring young married women 
just as important is the impact dual employment might be having 
on health care costs business in general is trying to reduce its 
benefits bill partly by shifting more of the cost to the employees 
but while business worries it is conceivable that the more 
serious cost to society might have less to do with business and 
more to do with the home 
