<TEXT>
in the late 1980s columbia savings 
and loan television ads showed a man in a suit standing high atop a 
graph lines on the chart zigzagged up to demonstrate the companys 
growth and strength 
id say things are headed in the right direction the 
pitchman said 
if the ads ran now the guy might have to stand in a junkyard 
a metaphor not only for columbia but also for other california 
sampls that diversified away from homemortgage lending during the 
deregulated frenzy of the last decade 
a third of the states 21 biggest thrifts are in danger of 
failing even in a state economy that is one of the largest and 
healthiest in the world 
why are so many california thrifts sick 
a big reason is bad investments made under deregulation 
columbias years of success for example were built on 
investments in junk bonds securities that paid high interest 
because they funded risky ventures many were sold by drexel 
burnham lambert incs junk bond purveyor michael milken to his 
friend and ally columbia chairman thomas spiegel 
columbias heap of junk far bigger than any other thrifts has 
fallen in value by at least 800 million because of that the sampl 
no longer meets federal standards for capital reserves its cash 
cushion against risk 
spiegel has resigned drexel is in bankruptcy court milken is 
indicted the market for the risky securities he helped pioneer has 
collapsed 
columbias new president edward harshfield is trying to sell 
the whole 35 billion junk bond package many observers dont 
think he can 
i just have a feeling columbia may be too far gone said 
bert ely an alexandria vabased financial industry consultant 
the no 2 junk bond investor san diegos imperial savings and 
loan was seized feb 23 the same day regulators took over 
huntington beachbased mercury savings mercury had many problems 
but fell into insolvency partly because of another bugbear for 
california thrifts a risky outofstate loan 
the number of thrifts in california boomed in the early 1980s 
after federal and state laws were loosened permitting sampls to make 
a range of investments unlike banks they originally had been 
allowed only to make loans for houses 
california has about 12 percent of the countrys population but 
29 percent of the sampl assets 
the state hasnt suffered the economic shocks of texas and other 
energy states which could partly blame the skidding oil business 
for their sampl problems or arizona where thrifts were buried when 
real estate prices slumped 
analysts regulators and industry officials instead blame shoddy 
managers who courted big depositors with high interest rates and 
made illconceived investments well beyond the golden states 
borders besides junk bonds california thrifts put money into duds 
ranging from stud horses to yugo cars 
honcho thrift entrepreneurs with little experience used their 
newfound license to write not just adjustable rate loans but 
commercial and industrial loans loans on vacant land all that 
goofy stuff california sampl commissioner william crawford said 
making matters worse many conservative lenders followed suit 
often trying to recoup losses from early fixedrate mortgage loans 
made at low rates a lot of the good monkeys copied the bad 
monkeys crawford said 
crawford and marion sandler president of world savings and loan 
association said trying to do business outside the state was the 
biggest problem 
first you dont know the territory and second youre the 
latest pigeon she said 
many california thrift managers wrongly assumed every market was 
as good as california said alex sheshunoff the head of an austin 
texasbased firm that tracks the thrift industry 
they thought they had geographical risk diversification 
sheshunoff said what they wound up with was a piece of every bad 
deal no matter where it was 
some of the more prominent thrifts that ventured outofstate 
include great american savings bank of san diego now seeking an 
investor or buyer after losing 124 million in 1989 largely 
because of commercial lending in arizona 
great westerns 1989 profits fell 60 percent because of a 200 
million reserve for losses on commercial realestate loans most of 
them outside california the company is regarded as healthy 
nonetheless 
irvinebased lincoln savings the notorious thrift that 
regulators say will cost 2 billion to bail out lost money on 
arizona real estate and junk bonds it is the biggest sampl collapse 
so far 
mercury said a soured loan on a hotel in tulsa okla helped 
push it into insolvency with assets of 216 billion it had a 
negative net worth of 33 million when seized 
san diegos imperial had assets of 97 billion and a negative 
net worth of 60 million when regulators seized it besides big 
junk bond holdings imperials problems included shaky car loans 
and backing the importer of the yugo a car us drivers shunned 
ely attributes many of the problems to simply too many sampls with 
too few solid franchises 
theres parallels to the steel industry said ely what 
were doing is trimming away obsolescence its the same trend 
you see in any mature industry 
