<TEXT>
the government presents its budget tuesday against 
a background of inflation and high interest rates that are 
threatening prime minister margaret thatchers prospects for 
reelection 
chancellor of the exchequer john major is not expected to 
produce any radical changes in his speech to parliament outlining 
the fiscal year ending march 1991 but he is expected to try and 
boost confidence in his existing tight monetary policy which has 
squeezed consumers and raised fears of recession 
base interest rates have risen to 15 percent sending home loan 
costs soaring while an unpopular new property tax that takes 
effect next month will raise many homeowners bills by a third 
inflation is 77 percent already the highest among the major 
industrialized nations and is forecast to rise to 9 percent the 
pound has weakened and the nations 1989 trade deficit was 34 
billion 
a tight budget likely will worsen mrs thatchers standing 
while economists fear it wont be tight enough to wring out 
stubborn inflation raising taxes would curb consumers ability to 
spend 
my view is that we need a very tight budget indeed said 
keith skeoch chief economist at the london investment firm james 
capel and co 
the spring budget statement outlines the governments revenue 
raising plans and is a principal platform for announcing economic 
policies and forecasts 
the government details its spending plans in an autumn 
statement last november major said spending would reach 179 
billion pounds the equivalent of 288 billion in the coming year 
critics say the economy overheated because of the 1988 tax cuts 
devised by thenchancellor nigel lawson lawson eliminated four of 
six tax brackets cutting the basic rate from 27 percent to 25 
percent and the top rate from 60 percent to 40 percent 
the cuts partly were aimed at preventing a recession after the 
1987 global stock market crash but since then the government has 
pushed up interest rates 11 times to double their decadelow 75 
percent of june 1988 
the hikes are intended to curb inflation which has more than 
doubled to 77 percent since january 1988 
there are fears that high interest rates might topple britain 
into a recession after eight straight years of economic growth 
major says britains economic growth should slow to 125 percent 
from 2 percent last year 
these are setbacks for the conservative government which took 
credit for curing the british disease of high interest rates 
and inflation 
now mrs thatcher who must call an election by mid1992 faces 
doubts about her economic stewardship 
the strategy has patently failed to work weve gone to a 
situation where a recession is almost necessary to slow 
inflation skeoch said 
gavyn davies a british economist with goldman sachs 
international said i think its working yes 
but it no longer looks like a thatcher economic miracle 
just last week the government reported that retail sales rose 
24 percent in february to an alltime high of 15 billion despite 
the higher interest rates 
neil kinnock leader of the opposition labor party claimed mrs 
thatchers policies are failing to manage demand they are 
increasing inflation they are decreasing manufacturing investment 
and they are clobbering every homebuyer in the country because of 
mortgage rates 
but the government said such economic figures can be erratic 
that the retail sales growth was slower than last years 4 percent 
and that economic indicators point to a slowdown 
mrs thatcher told parliament the high interest rates are 
working but declined to give assurances that they wont go any 
higher 
pessimists fear the government again will raise interest rates 
to prop up the pound whose fall is worsening inflation prospects 
sterling is trading at about 161 compared with 187 in december 
1988 
the foreign exchange and stock markets have been jittery over 
the economy mrs thatchers declining popularity in opinion polls 
and violent protests against the new property tax 
however there are bright spots unemployment has fallen to 56 
percent in february from a peak of 115 percent in june 1986 the 
government has a budget surplus of 155 billion for the first 11 
months of its current fiscal year the strikes that plagued british 
industry in the 1970s virtually have disappeared 
former conservative party chairman norman tebbit told reporters 
last week that interest rates almost certainly will fall by the end 
of 1990 because the government will have to ease the pressure as 
the next election approaches 
