<TEXT>
large bank holding companies have moved 
swiftly to take advantage of a loophole in the legal wall 
separating banking from the securities industry according to a 
congressional report 
bank holding companies under a regulation passed by the federal 
reserve board three years ago started underwriting a limited 
amount of some previously forbidden securities in the 
julyseptember quarter of 1988 
in that quarter four companies underwrote 123 billion in 
securities the general accounting office said in a report to the 
house banking oversight subcommittee 
by the julyseptember quarter of 1989 the latest period for 
which data was available 13 companies underwrote 687 billion up 
90 percent from the previous quarter and 460 percent from a year 
earlier 
ninetyeight percent of the securities involved were commercial 
paper shortterm debt issued by large publicly traded companies 
the figures also include municipal revenue bonds mortgagerelated 
securities and other assetbacked securities 
the gao said the bank activity represented about 19 percent of 
the combined markets in those securities 
another eight companies have gotten permission to receive 
underwriting what are termed ineligible securities but had not 
started yet the fed has also expanded the list of securities 
covered by the loophole to include corporate debt and is expected 
to soon approve the first bank underwriting of corporate stock 
the gao congress auditing and investigative agency said it 
was too soon to draw any conclusions about the profitability or 
riskiness of bank holding company affiliates involvement in 
securities 
so far the fed has limited the holding companies to deriving no 
more than 10 percent of their revenue from ineligible securities 
that restriction is in place to comply with the 1933 glasssteagall 
act 
the act separated commercial from investment banking in the wake 
of abuses thought to contribute to a wave of bank failures that 
followed the 1929 stock market crash 
next year congress is expected to reopen debate on whether and 
how to permit banks to move more broadly into the securities 
business 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

