<TEXT>
here are the major developments in the ual corp 
buyout story 
june 1989 nwa inc accepts a 365 billion bid for northwest 
airlines from an investor group led by alfred checci stirring 
takeover interest in airline companies 
august los angeles investor marvin davis offers 54 billion 
or 240 a share for ual corp the parent of united airlines he 
later sweetens the bid to 619 billion or 275 a share 
sept 14 ual directors accept a 675 billion offer or 300 a 
share from uniteds pilots management and british airways plc 
the offer includes labor and wage concessions 
sept 15 davis says he will match the offer and demand no 
labor concessions 
oct 13 the 675 billion takeover by pilots management and 
british airways collapses when financing fails on wall street the 
dow jones average of 30 industrials falls nearly 200 points 
oct 17 davis withdraws his matching bid for ual 
oct 20 british airways says it will no longer participate in 
takeover talks 
oct 30 united pilots without a contract since april 1988 
resume talks with the company 
oct 31 machinists union says it wont join davis in making a 
new offer for ual 
nov 1 investor saul steinberg tells the government he wants 
to buy 15 percent to 25 percent of ual stock 
nov 3 the investment group coniston partners says it has a 
97 percent stake in ual and wants to reduce the size of the board 
of directors 
jan 8 1990 ual directors tell financial advisers to consider 
a recapitalization of the company 
jan 24 uniteds three labor unions say they are willing to 
buy 75 percent of the stock directors say it is not a formal 
acquisition bid and they tell their advisers to try to come up 
with a firm proposal 
march 19 ual unions and coniston partners announce a new 38 
billion offer 
