<TEXT>
as the tokyo stock exchange took one of its worst 
beatings ever monday a senior bank of japan official reiterated 
that the central banks key concern was inflation adding fuel to 
expectations for higher interest rates 
rattled by a stronger us dollar and speculation that an 
interest rate hike was imminent the exchanges nikkei stock 
average plunged 135320 points on monday a 415 percent tumble 
that marked its third biggest daily decline ever the close at 
3126324 points was the lowest for the nikkei stock average since 
jan 20 1989 
the decline continued tuesday after a short upswing the nikkei 
was down 69129 points or 221 percent at 3057195 in early 
trading it was the first time the index dropped under 31000 even 
temporarily since jan 9 1989 
the nikkeis decline on monday was at least partly tied to the 
growing strength of the us dollar against the japanese yen which 
could help fuel inflation in japan 
the bank of japan has attempted to stall the dollars rise in 
recent months by selling billions of dollars in the currency 
markets 
there also is speculation that the central bank will hike its 
benchmark discount rate to support the yen and fight inflation 
in the stock market on monday many investors appeared to be 
selling shares as though a rate rise were imminent 
keiichi nishida of kidder peabody securities said because 
mondays drop was not the result of panic selling there is a 
widely shared fear in the market that share prices may fall even 
further until they really hit the bottom 
but at this point no one knows where the bottom really is 
he said 
the bank of japan official who spoke to reporters monday on 
condition of anonymity said the stock markets rapid rise last 
year set the stage for a downward correction he also said that 
if the market was having trouble finding its appropriate level it 
is due to political factors and speculation 
the official acknowledged that the correction which so far 
this year has cut nearly 20 percent from the nikkei average had 
been larger than anticipated but he reiterated that the central 
banks primary concerns were elsewhere particularly in controlling 
inflation 
the bank of japan official said that although the central bank 
cant create specific exchange rate levels its repeated 
intervention should influence the market over time 
nevertheless the dollar continued rising monday it closed at a 
threeyear high of 15355 yen up 105 yen from last fridays close 
dealers said the bank of japan made largescale interventions 
monday to stem the yens fall one dealer with daiichi kangyo bank 
said the central bank bought at least 1 billion worth of yen 
monday 
the yens prolonged weakness coupled with signs of inflation 
has convinced many stock and exchange market participants that 
another discount rate hike is looming higher interest rates tend 
to bolster the yen but depress stock prices 
the bank of japan official appeared to give credence to the view 
that the bank will raise its key rate soon admitting that the 
timing of the rate hike is difficult he said it may be too late 
to act when the indicators are flashing 
after several years of stability the bank raised the discount 
rate its interest on loans to commercial banks three times last 
year bringing it to 425 percent from 25 percent 
masaaki tanahashi a currency dealer with mitsui bank said some 
market players were hesitant to buy the yen until the bank of japan 
actually raises the discount rate 
the daiichi kangyo dealer who requested anonymity said i 
would not be surprised to see the dollar surpass the 154yen mark 
before the interest rate hike actually happens 
</TEXT>
